go under
the wall? Is it going to go
around the wall?

34:29.367 --> 34:32.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, my concern is, there is
probably a better
way to do it.

34:32.938 --> 34:37.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The long-term
solution is to
find and remove the uranium fuel
from the

34:37.943 --> 34:44.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
four reactors affected. They
have started
the process by removing fuel
that was in underwater

34:45.016 --> 34:47.385 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
storage.

34:47.419 --> 34:52.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At unit four, which was powered
down when
the tsunami hit, they built a
structure over

34:52.257 --> 34:59.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the damaged reactor, using it as
a platform
to carefully pluck out more than
1,500 fuel

34:59.397 --> 35:02.334 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
assemblies.

35:02.367 --> 35:08.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in units one, two and three,
where the
reactor cores all melted down,
radiation levels

35:08.173 --> 35:11.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
