35:27.025 --> 35:30.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LAKE BARRETT: Is it in one big
vertical lump
on the floor underneath it, or
did it come

35:30.895 --> 35:36.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
down and flow like lava in a
volcano and move
out to the sides? We don't know
yet.

35:37.002 --> 35:42.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: TEPCO has turned
to a team
of scientists and engineers from
the Los Alamos

35:42.674 --> 35:49.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
National Laboratory for some
assistance. They
are helping build a device
designed to see

35:49.681 --> 35:54.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
through the walls of the reactor
buildings
and hopefully make what looks
like three-dimensional

35:55.020 --> 35:58.656 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
X-rays of the reactor cores.

35:58.690 --> 36:06.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These long cylinders are able to
detect muons,
subatomic particles created in
space by quasars

36:06.398 --> 36:14.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and supernovas that rain down on
Earth. Muons
are stopped, slowed or deflected
depending

36:14.139 --> 36:21.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on the density of the matter
they are passing
through. And uranium is very
dense.

36:21.546 --> 36:25.483 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Physicist Chris Morris leads the
team.

36:25.517 --> 36:28.720 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CHRIS MORRIS, Los Alamos
National Laboratory:
You can reconstruct the amount
of material

36:28.753 --> 36:34.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at the core in the reactor. And
we can actually
measure if there's any uranium
there, if there's

36:34.526 --> 36:36.694 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a lot of uranium there, how much
is left.

36:36.728 --> 36:40.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The detectors
will be run for
months to give engineers the
sharpest possible

36:40.965 --> 36:44.469 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
picture inside a very hazardous
place.

36:44.502 --> 36:48.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS MORRIS: Human beings
aren't going in
there anytime soon. The
radiation levels are

36:48.106 --> 36:50.875 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
very high. It kills robots.

36:50.909 --> 36:56.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The robots they
have tried
here so far have offered up
glimpses inside

36:56.047 --> 37:02.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
