failing in
the face of a bombardment of
radiation.

37:02.987 --> 37:06.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Japanese robotics engineers have
their work
cut out for them.

37:06.257 --> 37:10.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LAKE BARRETT: I believe it can
be done. It
can be done safely and it can be
done successfully.

37:10.628 --> 37:13.231 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But nothing of this magnitude
has ever been
done by mankind.

37:13.264 --> 37:18.670 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NAOHIRO MASUDA (through
translator): I feel
very reassured that, in the next
30 or 40

37:18.703 --> 37:23.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
years, people from all over the
world will
gather in Fukushima to work and
research the

37:23.274 --> 37:28.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
decommissioning. I'm hoping it
will become
a very lively place.

37:28.413 --> 37:37.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Fukushima five
years later,
they have made progress here,
but it is just

37:37.922 --> 37:45.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
