again, but I realize
that what I'm doing is totally
different than

41:22.714 --> 41:26.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what I have done before. It's
more related
to what we are facing.

41:26.851 --> 41:32.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Another voice,
that of poetry,
which has always had an honored
place in Arabic

41:32.256 --> 41:34.092 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
culture.

41:34.125 --> 41:40.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ghada Alatrash is a Syrian
writer and translator
now earning a doctorate at the
University

41:40.832 --> 41:42.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of Calgary in Canada.

41:42.567 --> 41:49.006 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
GHADA ALATRASH,
Writer/Translator: Syrian
poetry today is an outcry. It is
a plea to

41:49.040 --> 41:54.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
humanity. It embodies that human
tragedy,
the raw pain, the loss and the
defeat.

41:54.278 --> 42:01.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Alatrash is from
Sweida, in
the south of Syria, and has
translated the

42:01.252 --> 42:13.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
work of Najat Abdul Samad, a
friend who remains
in their shared hometown. She
read us the

42:13.631 --> 42:17.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
beginning of the poem "When I Am
Overcome
With Weakness."

42:17.535 --> 42:25.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GHADA ALATRASH: "When I am
overcome with weakness,
I bandage my heart with a Syrian
woman's patience

42:25.076 --> 42:29.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in adversity. I bandage it with
December's
frozen tree roots, trees that
have sworn to

42:29.414 --> 42:31.349 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
blossom in March or April."

42:31.382 --> 42:40.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And then there is
this, a documentary
titled "The Cow Farm," about a
farmer on the

42:40.291 --> 42:42.126 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
